 a year he had rebuilt the family's finances as a New York stockbroker.","number":1},{"category":"business","header":"He built 'Samarkand,' a vast Carolina farm","body":"Naming it for the Asian city his father had visited, Raphael Welles built Samarkand, a two-thousand-acre showplace in the North Carolina sandhills. He set out twenty-four thousand peach trees and bred horses before failed crops forced him to sell.","number":2},{"category":"religion","header":"A Bahá'í who spoke for the faith","body":"From 1938 Raphael Welles lectured on the Bahá'í Faith across New York and as far as Idaho, and in 1948 served as a Bahá'í delegate to a United Nations religious conference. His parents had hosted 'Abdu'l-Bahá in 1912.","number":3}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"in_law","related_id":"X03114","display_label":"was his father-in-law; Union general who led troops into Richmond"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Raphael Welles","last_name":"Pumpelly","married_names":[],"display_name":"Raphael Welles Pumpelly","gender":"male","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780758541/18514327_1449951758_fascop.jpg"},"military_service":[],"slug":"raphael-welles-pumpelly-1881"},"I01543":{"id":"I01543","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"female","birth":{"year":1883,"month":6,"day":3,"city":"New York","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1963,"month":9,"day":27,"city":"Los Angeles","state":"California","country":"United States"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":true,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_id":"X03114","father_name":"Brig. Gen. Edward Hastings Ripley","mother_id":"X03115","mother_name":"Amelia Dyckman Van Doren Ripley"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"TD0337","spouse_name":"Raphael Welles Pumpelly","children_ids":["TD0345","TD0346","TD0347"],"notes":"Divorced 1942."}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"family","header":"A general's granddaughter who married a Pumpelly","body":"Amelie Sybil Van Doren Ripley was a daughter of the Civil War general Edward Hastings Ripley. She married Raphael Welles Pumpelly in a celebrated 1909 double wedding at New York's Grace Church.","number":1},{"category":"character","header":"Her lavish living drained the family fortune","body":"Amelie's spending, including gifts to the Christian Science church, helped push the Pumpellys toward ruin by 1918. Her 1925 separation from Raphael Welles, on grounds of infidelity, drew newspaper coverage across several states.","number":2}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Amelie Sybil","last_name":"Ripley","married_names":[],"display_name":"Amelie Sybil Van Doren Ripley","gender":"female"},"military_service":[],"slug":"amelie-sybil-ripley-1883"},"TD0334":{"id":"TD0334","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":true,"gender":"male","birth":{"year":1837,"month":9,"day":8,"city":"Owego","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1923,"month":8,"day":10,"city":"Newport","state":"Rhode Island","country":"United States"},"burial":{},"residence":{},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_john_talcott":6,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["science","exploration"],"notable_blurb":"Geologist and explorer of Asia's interior","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raphael_Pumpelly","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"parents":{"father_id":"I01523","father_name":"William Pumpelly","mother_id":"T01812","mother_name":"Mary H. Welles"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_name":"Eliza F. Shepard","date_year":1869,"spouse_id":"I01540","children_ids":["TD0335","TD0336","TD0337"]}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"science","header":"He mapped Asia's deserts for American science","body":"Trained as a mining engineer, Raphael Pumpelly surveyed mineral country across Japan, China, and Mongolia in the 1860s and crossed the Gobi Desert. His later expeditions into Russian Central Asia searched for the origins of agriculture and early civilization."},{"number":2,"category":"science","header":"He tied windblown dust to climate history","body":"Pumpelly's studies of loess, the fine wind-laid soil of northern China, helped show how such deposits record ancient climate. At home he directed the northern transcontinental railroad survey and led major government geological surveys."},{"category":"career","header":"He held Harvard's first chair in mining","body":"From 1866 to 1875 Pumpelly served as Harvard's first professor of mining, between expeditions that carried him around the world. He later organized the economic-geology division of the new U.S. Geological Survey and directed its New England branch.","number":3},{"category":"science","header":"His Anau dig pushed Central Asian history back","body":"In 1903 Pumpelly led a Carnegie-funded expedition to the Anau mounds in Turkmenistan, uncovering a settlement he dated to about 4500 BCE. The mineral pumpellyite, found in Michigan's copper country, was later named in his honor.","number":4},{"category":"legacy","header":"He blazed the Pumpelly Trail up Monadnock","body":"From his summer place at Dublin, New Hampshire, Pumpelly cut a ridge trail to the summit of Mount Monadnock that still carries his name. He spent his last decades at Newport and presided over the Geological Society of America in 1905.","number":5}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","display_label":"descends from Springfield's founder William Pynchon","related_id":"Y00004","link_text":"Hon. William Pynchon"},{"type":"family_connection","display_label":"descends from Connecticut governor Thomas Welles","related_id":"X02354","link_text":"Gov. Thomas Welles"},{"type":"parallel_careers","display_label":"the mineralogist in whose system pumpellyite is classed","related_id":"X00898","link_text":"Edward Salisbury Dana"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Raphael","last_name":"Pumpelly","married_names":[],"display_name":"Raphael Pumpelly","gender":"male","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780757921/18514323_ba588cd9-8d5f-46cb-89d2-794a87890734_j2tjyt.jpg"},"military_service":[],"education":[{"school_name":"Bergakademie Freiberg","dates":"1856-1859","type":"graduate","notes":"Mining engineering."}],"career":[{"role":"Geologist & explorer","organization":"Surveys of Japan, China, Mongolia","start_year":1861,"notes":"Mining & geological surveys."},{"role":"Director","organization":"Northern Transcontinental Survey","notes":"Railroad route survey."}],"slug":"raphael-pumpelly-1837"},"I01540":{"id":"I01540","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"female","birth":{"year":1840,"month":3,"day":14,"city":"Dorchester","county":"Suffolk County","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1915,"month":2,"day":5,"city":"Newport","county":"Newport County","state":"Rhode Island","country":"United States"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":true,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_name":"Otis Shepard","mother_name":"Ann Pope"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"TD0334","spouse_name":"Raphael Pumpelly","marriage_year":1869,"marriage_place":"Dorchester, Massachusetts","children_ids":["TD0335","TD0336","TD0337"]}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"arts","header":"John Singer Sargent painted her portrait","body":"In 1887 John Singer Sargent painted a waist-length portrait of Eliza Shepard Pumpelly, now held by the Berkshire Museum. She had married the geologist Raphael Pumpelly in 1869 and shared his homes at Newport and in the New Hampshire hills.","number":1}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[{"artwork_id":"ART070","role":"subject"}],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"artifact","related_id":"I01660","display_label":"also drawn by John Singer Sargent"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Eliza Frances","last_name":"Shepard","married_names":["Pumpelly"],"display_name":"Eliza Frances Shepard Pumpelly","gender":"female","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780758136/1280px-John_Singer_Sargent_-_Portrait_of_Mrs._Raphael_Pumpelly_-_Google_Art_Project_itkol9.jpg"},"military_service":[],"slug":"eliza-frances-shepard-1840"},"X03114":{"id":"X03114","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"male","birth":{"year":1839,"month":11,"day":11,"city":"Rutland","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1915,"month":9,"day":14,"city":"Rutland","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":true},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["military","business"],"notable_blurb":"Union general who led troops into Richmond","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_H._Ripley","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"parents":{},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X03115","spouse_name":"Amelia Dyckman Van Doren Ripley","marriage_year":1878,"children_ids":["I01543"]}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"military","header":"He led the first troops into fallen Richmond","body":"A Vermont colonel who rose to brevet brigadier general, Ripley commanded the brigade ordered to occupy Richmond after its surrender in April 1865. His men fought the fires, stopped the looting, and restored order in the captured Confederate capital.","number":1},{"category":"military","header":"He warned Lincoln of a plot in Richmond","body":"When Lincoln visited Richmond days after its fall, Ripley learned of an assassination plot and urged him to take greater precautions. Lincoln declined, saying it mattered more to be seen among the people as a sign the war was ending.","number":2},{"category":"military","header":"He was captured in the Harper's Ferry surrender","body":"In September 1862 Ripley was among the twelve thousand men surrendered at Harper's Ferry, the largest Union capitulation of the war. Exchanged months later, he returned to lead the 9th Vermont through Virginia and North Carolina.","number":3},{"category":"career","header":"He built marble, railroads, and a hotel","body":"After the war Ripley ran the family's Vermont marble business, built New York's Holland House Hotel, and developed New Jersey's Raritan River Railroad. He also helped found a steamship line to Brazil and led two Rutland banks.","number":4},{"category":"legacy","header":"His war diary became a published book","body":"Ripley lectured and wrote on his war years, printing his account of the capture of Richmond in 1907. His diary appeared in 1960 as Vermont General, decades after his death.","number":5}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_connection","display_label":"shared the Harper's Ferry garrison of September 1862","related_id":"HD3720","link_text":"Sgt-Maj Giles Hooker Cowles"},{"type":"in_law","related_id":"TD0337","display_label":"married his daughter Amelie"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Edward Hastings","last_name":"Ripley","married_names":[],"display_name":"Brig. Gen. Edward Hastings Ripley","gender":"male","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780761268/Edward_Hastings_Ripley-resized_h4ioxa.png"},"military_service":[{"war":"American Civil War","active_in_war":true,"rank":"Colonel; Brevet Brigadier General","unit":"9th Vermont Infantry; 1st Brigade, 3rd Division, XXIV Corps","notes":"Led the Union occupation of Richmond, April 1865.","war_id":"WAR006"}],"slug":"edward-hastings-ripley-1839"},"X03115":{"id":"X03115","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"female","birth":{"year":1845,"month":10,"day":26,"city":"New York","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1931,"month":4,"day":1,"city":"Rutland","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"is_easter_egg":true},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X03114","spouse_name":"Brig. Gen. Edward Hastings Ripley","marriage_year":1878,"children_ids":["I01543"]}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"family","header":"Her family's name marked a New York hotel","body":"Amelia Dyckman Van Doren married Edward Hastings Ripley in 1878, and her family owned the Holland House Hotel he built in New York. The couple raised two daughters who married in a celebrated 1909 double wedding.","number":1}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Amelia Dyckman","last_name":"Van Doren","married_names":[],"display_name":"Amelia Dyckman Van Doren Ripley","gender":"female"},"military_service":[],"slug":"amelia-dyckman-van-doren-1845"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}